### Phase 3: Autonomous Retry Loop (The Killer Feature)

This is what makes MicrOps unlike anything else on the market.

#### [MODIFY] `backend/src/services/build/builder.service.ts`

After a build failure, instead of just showing the diagnostic report and waiting for the user to click "Apply Fix":

1. The diagnostic engine returns a `fixAction`.
2. **If the fix is a safe, deterministic patch** (e.g., `PATCH_INSTALL_CMD`, `SET_BUILD_CMD`, `UPGRADE_RUNTIME`), the worker **automatically applies the fix to the project record in the database** and **re-queues a new build job** — all without user intervention.
3. Cap the auto-retry at **2 attempts** (original + 2 retries = 3 total tries max) to prevent infinite loops.
4. Emit structured SSE events so the frontend shows the user exactly what happened:
   - `[AI Agent] ❌ Build failed: Peer dependency conflict detected.`
   - `[AI Agent] 🔧 Auto-applying fix: npm install --legacy-peer-deps`
   - `[AI Agent] 🔄 Retrying build (attempt 2 of 3)...`
5. If all 3 attempts fail, show the final diagnostic report with the manual "Apply Fix" button as a last resort.

#### [MODIFY] `backend/src/controllers/build.controller.ts`

No changes needed — the SSE stream already handles `build-progress` events, so the retry loop logs will automatically flow to the frontend in real-time.

---

### Phase 4: Frontend & Backend Deployment Separation

#### [MODIFY] `backend/src/services/preflight/detectors.service.ts`

Add smart classification so MicrOps knows whether a repo is a **frontend SPA**, **backend API**, or **fullstack monorepo**:

| Signal | Classification | Behavior |
|--------|---------------|----------|
| Has `vite.config.*` or `next.config.*` + no `express`/`fastapi` | **Frontend SPA** | Build → serve static files via `serve -s dist` |
| Has `express`, `fastapi`, `@nestjs/core`, `django` | **Backend API** | Build → run `npm start` / `uvicorn` |
| Has both frontend framework + backend framework | **Fullstack Monorepo** | Warn user, ask which directory to deploy |
| Has `Dockerfile` | **Custom Container** | Trust the user's Dockerfile completely |

This classification will be stored in the project record and used by the Dockerfile generator to pick the optimal container strategy.

